<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-02-04T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-02-04T23:00:00-05:00" n="82" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d82">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94/1953a: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Substance]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-02-04T23:00:00-05:00">February 4, 1941—11
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>80. Reference is made to your No. 126 of January 27, 7 p.m., final
                            sentence in paragraph No. 1. Assuming that you lack an official text,
                            the Department would be interested in a close comparison by the Embassy
                            of available press reports in order to determine whether Minister
                            Matsuoka indicated that the attackers at Marco Polo Bridge were the
                            Japanese.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>